Ant Design provides responsive design support with its built-in grid system. You can use the `Col` component's `xs`, `sm`, `md`, `lg`, and `xl` props to define how many columns an element should occupy at different screen sizes. 

Here's an example code snippet that demonstrates how to change content based on screen size using Ant Design:

```
import { Col, Row } from 'antd';

const MyComponent = () => {
  const content = <div>Default content</div>;
  const mobileContent = <div>Mobile content</div>;

  return (
    <div>
      <Row>
        <Col xs={24} md={18}>
          {content}
        </Col>
        <Col xs={24} md={6}>
          {mobileContent}
        </Col>
      </Row>
    </div>
  );
};
```

This code uses the `Col` component's `xs` prop to define how many columns an element should occupy on extra small screens (mobile devices) and the `md` prop to define how many columns it should occupy on medium screens (tablets and desktops). In this case, `content` is the default content that will be shown on medium and large screens, and `mobileContent` is the content that will be shown on extra small screens.

With this setup, when the screen size is extra small, the `Col` with `mobileContent` will take up the full width of the screen (all 24 columns), and the `Col` with `content` will take up 18 columns on medium screens and larger. When the screen size is medium or larger, the `Col` with `content` will take up 18 columns and the `Col` with `mobileContent` will not be visible. 

You can adjust the values of the `xs`, `sm`, `md`, `lg`, and `xl` props to suit your specific needs for responsiveness.

You can show or hide items based on screen size using Ant Design's `hidden` and `visible` props. Here's an example code snippet that demonstrates how to show or hide elements based on screen size:

```
import { Button } from 'antd';

const MyComponent = () => {
  return (
    <div>
      <Button type="primary" size="large" visible={{ sm: false }}>
        Large Button
      </Button>
      <Button type="primary" size="large" hidden={{ sm: true }}>
        Large Button
      </Button>
    </div>
  );
};
```

This code uses the `visible` prop on the first `Button` to hide it when the screen size is small (`sm` or smaller) and the `hidden` prop on the second `Button` to show it only when the screen size is small. 

The values of the `visible` and `hidden` props can be objects with keys matching the screen size breakpoints (`xs`, `sm`, `md`, `lg`, and `xl`). The values should be boolean values that determine whether the element should be visible or hidden at that screen size breakpoint.

Note that this feature requires importing the `ConfigProvider` component from `antd`. You can also set the default breakpoint for all components using the `ConfigProvider`'s `breakpoint` prop.

