Yes, you can achieve the desired effect using custom CSS media queries as an alternative to the Ant Design grid system. Here's an example code snippet that demonstrates how to show or hide elements based on screen size using CSS media queries:

```
import { Button } from 'antd';

const MyComponent = () => {
  return (
    <div>
      <Button type="primary" size="large" className="visible-sm">
        Large Button
      </Button>
      <Button type="primary" size="large" className="hidden-sm">
        Large Button
      </Button>
    </div>
  );
};
```

In this code, the `visible-sm` class will be added to the first `Button` only on screens smaller than or equal to 576px wide (the small screen breakpoint in Ant Design). The `hidden-sm` class will be added to the second `Button` only on screens larger than 576px wide. 

To achieve this, you will need to define appropriate CSS class styles for each media query breakpoint. Here's an example CSS code snippet that demonstrates how to define these styles:

```
@media only screen and (max-width: 576px) {
  .visible-sm {
    display: block;
  }

  .hidden-sm {
    display: none;
  }
}

@media only screen and (min-width: 577px) {
  .visible-sm {
    display: none;
  }

  .hidden-sm {
    display: block;
  }
}
```

In this CSS code, the first media query defines styles for screens that are smaller than or equal to 576px wide. The `visible-sm` class is set to `display: block` to show the element, and the `hidden-sm` class is set to `display: none` to hide the element. The second media query defines styles for screens that are larger than 576px wide, and the styles for the `visible-sm` and `hidden-sm` classes are reversed. 

You can adjust the media query breakpoints and class names according to your specific needs.

To make this Ant Design `Sider` component closed by default, you can set the `collapsed` and `defaultCollapsed` props to `true`. Here's an example code snippet:

```
import { Layout } from 'antd';

const { Sider } = Layout;

const MyComponent = () => {
  const [collapsed, setCollapsed] = useState(true);

  return (
    <div>
      <Layout>
        <Sider trigger={null} collapsible collapsed={collapsed} defaultCollapsed={true}>
          {/** your Sider content goes here */}
        </Sider>
        {/** the rest of your layout goes here */}
      </Layout>
    </div>
  );
};
```

In this code, the `collapsed` state is initialized to `true` so that the `Sider` component is closed by default. The `collapsed` prop is also set to `true` to ensure that the `Sider` component is correctly initialized with its default state, and the `defaultCollapsed` prop is set to `true` to specify the default collapsed state.

Note that you may wish to adjust your layout to account for the fact that the `Sider` component is closed by default. For example, you may need to add a button or other navigation element to open the `Sider` component.
